#Text=Wikinews interviews former Matilda 's player Sarah Walsh about Australian women 's soccer
#Text=Tuesday , December 17 , 2013
#Text=Earlier this week , Wikinews interviewed Sarah Walsh , a former Australian women 's national soccer team ( Matilidas ) player , about women 's football in the country .
#Text=The Australian women 's team is currently ranked ninth by FIFA , down one spot from the previous quarter when they were tied at eighth with the North Korea women 's national football team .
#Text=Meanwhile , Australia 's men ( Socceroos ) are currently ranked 59th in the world , between the Burkina Faso and Slovakia national football team .
#Text=Walsh retired from the national team in September of last year , after scoring 32 goals in 71 appearances .
#Text=She was on Matildas side that qualified for the World Cup for the first time while playing in the Asian Football Confederation instead of the Oceania Football Confederation .
#Text=She also played in two World Cup quarter-finals for the team .
#Text=Playing in Australia 's top level domestic league , the W-League , she won the league championship in 2009 .
#Text=She retired from the league this year .
#Text=Walsh played professionally in the United States for Sky Blue FC and Saint Louis Athletica .
#Text=Sarah Walsh playing for the Matilidas against Italy in a friendly international in 2009 .
#Text=Image : Camw .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) :
#Text=The Socceroos are ranked 59th by FIFA .
#Text=The Matildas are ranked 8th by FIFA in the latest rankings .
#Text=Should media coverage correlate to team performance and internationally rankings ?
#Text=Is there an element of tall poppy syndrome in the coverage of the Socceros ?
#Text=What other factors can be used to explain the relative differences in media attention other than performance ?
#Text=Sarah Walsh : Traditionally in Australia , male sports have dominated media coverage .
#Text=Slowly we are seeing women 's sports feature more frequently in mainstream media publications .
#Text=There is a growing interest in women 's sports , especially women 's national teams in general here in Australia .
#Text=With time , the public will be exposed to more female sports on a daily basis and perhaps will build the same affections for these female sports .
#Text=As a teenager , I was exposed to NRL living in Sydney , so naturally I have a strong interest in this game along with football ( soccer ) .
#Text=Young female teenagers today , have the option to turn the TV on and watch the W-league and follow their heroes .
#Text=I believe in 5 – 10 years ' time we will see a cultural change with regards to media coverage and gender bias .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) :
#Text=What 's the difference in style of play between the men and women 's national teams ?

#Text=Sarah Walsh : Men They appear to play a possession-based game working at effective possession combined with a developing system of pressing using our natural athleticism and high work rate as well as our cultural mental strength .

#Text=Sarah Walsh : Women The women seem to employ a more defensive and well organized " block " making it hard for teams to play through particularly in the middle and our back thirds utilizing transitional moments ( BPO – BP ) to good effect with quick attacks through the natural speed of certain players .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) :
#Text=Why are the Matildas more successful in international competitions and ranking wise than the Socceroos ?
#Text=Sarah Walsh :
#Text=There could be a number of contributing factors .
#Text=One in particular could be dues to financial reasons .
#Text=Given there is more financial support for men 's national teams globally in general , I believe the competition across the board is more extensive .
#Text=Due to this , there are more teams that compete at a higher level , so effectively this would make it difficult for the Socceroos to reach the same ranking as Matildas .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) :
#Text=Why do you think men do n't watch the Matildas in the same numbers as they watch the Socceroos ?
#Text=Sarah Walsh :
#Text=Answer similar to question 1 .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) : Does the media feed into traditional Australian gender stereotypes by not covering elite women 's sports ?
#Text=Sarah Walsh : Similar to question 1 .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) : What is your role in sports ?
#Text=Journalist ? Academic ? Sport administrator ? Player ?
#Text=Please provide one to two sentence biography to contextualize your answers .
#Text=Sarah Walsh : I started playing football at 5 years of age .
#Text=I made my debut for the Matildas at 21 ( 2004 – 2012 )
#Text=I have spent the past two years working in community football at FFA delivering a Drug and Alcohol program .
#Text=I am currently the Women 's Football Coordinator and Female Elite Player mentor at FFA .
#Text=Actually on wikipedia if you would like to cut and paste all that info !
